    "summary": "The Etruscan Decline (c. 500–264 BC) was the gradual contraction and absorption of the Etruscan civilization of central Italy, which had once dominated the Italian peninsula from the Po Valley to Campania, as it succumbed to Celtic invasions from the north, Greek pressures in the south, and above all the relentless expansion of Rome — a city originally shaped by Etruscan culture.\n\nEtruscan civilization had flourished from roughly 900 to 500 BC, producing sophisticated art, urban planning, religious practices, and the alphabet (derived from Greek) that the Romans adopted and eventually transmitted to Western Europe. Etruscan kings (the Tarquins) had ruled Rome itself before the founding of the Roman Republic. The decline involved several overlapping processes: the Gauls' invasion of the Po Valley around 390 BC destroyed many northern Etruscan cities; defeat at the Battle of Cumae (474 BC) to Syracuse ended Etruscan naval power and influence in Campania; and Rome's ongoing wars with Etruscan cities like Veii (taken in 396 BC after a decade-long siege) steadily reduced Etruscan territory. The final Etruscan cities were absorbed into the Roman state by the mid-3rd century BC. The Etruscan language died out by around 100 AD, though many Etruscan religious practices, architectural traditions, and artistic motifs survived in Roman culture.",
